        private final Lazy<Maybe<T>> head
        ATTRIBUTE: head This attribute stores the value of the head, which is a Maybe object, wrapped in a Lazy object. This means that it is only evaluated when needed, and evaluated once.

        ATTRIBUTE: EMPTY_LIST This attribute is an empty list, that can be used to indicate that the list is empty, or to mark the end of an finite list. Needed for truncating the list, or creating an empty list.

      • InfiniteList

        private InfiniteList​(T head,
                     Producer<InfiniteList<T>> tail)
        CONSTRUCTOR METHOD 2: InfiniteList() This method is for taking in the head, a parameter of type T and a producer tail, of type InfiniteList of type T and initialising an instance of InfiniteList. Usually called by the factory method iterate().
        Parameters:
        head - The starting value of the infinite list.
        tail - The producer required to populate the remaining elements of the infinite list.

      • InfiniteList

        private InfiniteList​(Lazy<Maybe<T>> head,
                     Lazy<InfiniteList<T>> tail)
        CONSTRUCTOR METHOD 3: InfiniteList() This method is for taking in the head, an instance of Lazy of Maybe of type parameter T, and a tail, an instance of Lazy of InfiniteList of type parameter T, and initialising an instance of InfiniteList. Usually called by the factory method generate()
        Parameters:
        head - The starting value of infinite list wrapped in a Lazy, that wraps a Maybe object of type T. This is so that the infinite list can exhibit laziness.
        tail - The tail is a producer that produces an infinite list, which is wrapped in a Lazy object, so that the tail would be produced only when called upon and produced only once.

      • iterate

        public static <T> InfiniteList<T> iterate​(T seed,
                                          Transformer<T,​T> next)
        FACTORY METHOD: iterate This factory method produces an infinite list with values conforming to an equation defined by the transformer "next" e.g. [[1] [[2] [[3] ...]]] where transformer is x + 1.
        Type Parameters:
        T - The type variable of teh infinite list defined.
        Parameters:
        seed - The starting value of the infinite list.
        next - The transformer that transform the first value, into the next value required for the next element of the infinite list.
        Returns:
        InfiniteList Returns an InfiniteList

        public InfiniteList<T> filter​(BooleanCondition<? super T> predicate)

      • limit

        public InfiniteList<T> limit​(long n)
        METHOD: limit(n) This method would truncate the infinite list after a specified n elements. Elements that are of Maybe.None type are not counted, and looked over.
        Parameters:
        n - The specified length of the list to be truncated
        Returns:
        InfiniteList It returns a truncated finite list, of the type InfiniteList with an EmptyList at the end of it.

      • takeWhile

        public InfiniteList<T> takeWhile​(BooleanCondition<? super T> predicate)
        METHOD: takeWhile(predicate) This method would run through the list and check if each element fulfils the predicate. If it fails the test, it would truncate the list.
        Parameters:
        predicate - The testing condition that the element of the list needs to fulfil.
        Returns:
        InfiniteList The method returns an finite list truncated at the first instance of an element failing the predicate. The type of the finite list is of InfiniteList type.

      • isEmpty

        public boolean isEmpty()
        METHOD: isEmpty() This method returns false for a normal infinite list as there are things inside the list. However, this method is overrided in the nested child class EmptyList, and there it would return true.
        Returns:
        boolean The method returns false for a normal infinite list.

      • reduce

        public <U> U reduce​(U identity,
                    Combiner<U,​? super T,​U> accumulator)
        METHOD: reduce(identity, accumulator) This method applies the lambda function accumulator repeatedly on the elements of the InfiniteList (finite) until it reduces the list to a single value. It is a terminal operation.
        Type Parameters:
        U - The type variable of the output value
        Parameters:
        identity - The variable to be combined with the element of the list. It is updated by the result of the combination of a current element with the identity.
        accumulator - The function to how to combine the identity with with the current element.
        Returns:
        U The method returns a single value.
